{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"Own the Pass-3 **deterministic novelty score + rising-floor drop rule** (task 3). Consume the\ntask-150b novelty score (`decide.novelty` / `verify.score_novelty`, both landed by 150b) and the\ntask-ec89 remediation-mode eligibility decision, then apply the deterministic floor. This task\nadds the drop math, the narrowed coverage, the sidecar write of dropped findings, the runtime\ndefaults, and the activation guard. (Note: `NOVELTY_SUBANSWERS`, `decide.novelty`, and\n`verify.score_novelty` are 150b deliverables already merged on this branch — a re-review that\ngrounds against `origin/main` will not see them; they exist in the work branch.)\n\n## Where the floor is applied (Pass-3 stays pure)\n\nThe floor is applied in the `_run_plan_review` WRAPPER (`src/rebar/llm/plan_review/__init__.py`),\nAFTER the deterministic verdict is produced and the ec89 eligibility decision is computed — NOT\ninside `orchestrator.pass3_over_findings` / the `plan_review_decide` workflow step (those stay\npure arithmetic with no LLM). So **no existing caller of `pass3_over_findings` changes**. The\nwrapper, when (and only when) eligible AND active, scores novelty over the surfaced advisory\nfindings (the droppable surface — blocking findings are high-priority and never dropped) via the\n150b sub-call, then moves the dropped findings out of `advisory` into the verdict's `dropped`\nbucket before the sidecar is emitted.\n\n## Drop rule (deterministic — no LLM holistic severity)\n\nA finding is dropped **iff** `novelty ≥ T_novel` AND `priority < floor`, where\n`priority = validity × impact` (the existing Pass-3 score). Carryover findings (novelty < T_novel)\nuse the normal threshold and must still be resolved. A novel high-priority finding is preserved\n(and may block). Implemented as a pure predicate `decide.rising_floor_drop(priority, novelty, *,\nt_novel, floor) -> bool` so it is unit-testable in isolation.\n\n## Defaults this task owns (derived, not guessed)\n\n- `verify.novelty_drop_threshold` (`T_novel`) = **0.7** — the runtime drop threshold,\n  config-overridable. House precision-first default; DISTINCT from the `discriminates_novelty`\n  eval bar (0.5 midpoint, task 150b). It is the documented default; per-corpus calibration is\n  explicitly deferred (epic \"Defaults & calibration\").\n- `verify.novelty_priority_floor` = a **scalar** constant (config-overridable), set to the **p40\n  impact percentile of the 245-event corpus** (≈ the \"below major\" band). It is a single number,\n  NOT a per-finding adaptive value: the drop test is `priority < floor`, and since\n  `priority = validity × impact`, the validity factor is already in `priority` — the floor itself\n  is a fixed impact-percentile scalar. `scripts/plan_review_impact_distribution.py` is extended to\n  print the impact PERCENTILES (incl. p40) so the chosen number is reproducible, not asserted.\n\n## Activation guard (the evidence gate — explicit mechanism)\n\nActivation is a **config key** `verify.novelty_drop_active` (default **False**). Mechanism (a):\nthe operator flips it to true MANUALLY after validating that 150b's `discriminates_novelty` eval\nhas cleared its bar (`rebar prompt eval plan-review-novelty` → the labeled pairs discriminate at\n`gate: at_least(2)`/`epochs:3` + `coverage_threshold:0.8`). Until then the gate runs full/\nun-floored. The drop path in `_run_plan_review` is reached only when ALL of: config\n`remediation_mode` on (ec89), the ec89 eligibility decision `eligible`, AND\n`novelty_drop_active` true — so the floor is triple-gated and inert by default. A test asserts the\ndrop rule is inert while `novelty_drop_active` is False even when eligibility holds.\n\n## Narrowed coverage + sidecar (observability)\n\nOn a narrowed verdict the wrapper sets, on `verdict[\"coverage\"]` (an open dict — no schema file\nchange), `narrowed: true`, `floored_criteria` (the criteria carried by the dropped findings), and\n`floored_finding_ids` (the dropped findings' ids). These keys are ABSENT on a normal/un-floored\nreview (byte-identical to today). Every dropped novel finding is moved into the verdict's\n`dropped` bucket, which `sidecar.build_payload` already persists (slimmed, WITH `norm_id`) — so\nsuppression is always observable and joinable by `norm_id`, and the dropped findings are NOT in\nthe surfaced verdict's `advisory`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Deterministic `decide.rising_floor_drop(priority, novelty, *, t_novel, floor)`: drop iff `novelty ≥ T_novel` AND `priority < floor`; carryover (novelty < T_novel) → normal threshold; novel high-priority → preserved (`src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/decide.py`)\n- [ ] `verify.novelty_drop_threshold` (default 0.7) and `verify.novelty_priority_floor` (a scalar = the stated corpus p40 impact percentile) are committed config-overridable defaults in `src/rebar/config.py`; `scripts/plan_review_impact_distribution.py` prints the impact percentiles the floor is derived from\n- [ ] Activation guard `verify.novelty_drop_active` (default False, operator-flipped after the 150b eval clears its bar); the floor is inert while False; a test asserts un-floored behavior when the flag is False even though eligibility holds\n- [ ] The floor is applied in `_run_plan_review` (post-verdict), gated on ec89 eligibility AND `novelty_drop_active` AND `remediation_mode`; `pass3_over_findings` and the `plan_review_decide` step are unchanged (Pass-3 stays pure)\n- [ ] Coverage on a narrowed verdict sets `narrowed: true` + `floored_criteria` + `floored_finding_ids` on `verdict[\"coverage\"]` (absent on a normal review)\n- [ ] Every dropped novel finding is moved to the verdict's `dropped` bucket (persisted to the `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar with `norm_id`), and removed from the surfaced `advisory`\n- [ ] Consumes task ec89's remediation-mode eligibility decision (`coverage[\"remediation\"]`); does NOT re-implement the freshness-window/precondition check\n- [ ] Offline tests (no live LLM): the pure drop predicate (all four quadrants), the inert-when-flag-False guard, the narrowed-coverage assembly + sidecar dropped bucket with an INJECTED novelty map (so no LLM call is needed to prove the wrapper)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782784389188122001,"uuid":"d1b32bac-77a3-4ad6-8fa8-dd06e18df3b3"}